engths. |\n| **D** | Responds adequately to unexpected events; can concentrate very well; solves problems extremely well; **takes responsibility seriously** (explicit responsibility). | Moody, regarded as a loner, arrogant, weak leadership, hot temper, know\u2011it\u2011all attitude. No explicit stress\u2011handling or reliability statements; no teamwork strengths. |\n**Evaluation against the selection criteria**\n1. **Reliability & Responsibility** \u2013 Only D has an explicit responsibility statement; C\u2019s \u201cconcern for others\u201d suggests a responsibility mindset but is not a direct claim. A, B, and C lack any explicit reliability or responsibility statements.\n2. **Technical & Cognitive Competence** \u2013 All candidates are strong in different technical areas. C\u2019s combination of rapid correct decisions, high attention, and technical understanding aligns well with the cognitive demands of long\u2011haul flights.\n3. **Calmness, Judgment & Performance Under Pressure** \u2013 Explicitly documented for B (handles stress well), C (calm in crisis, quick correct decisions), and D (responds adequately to unexpected events). A has no explicit evidence.\n4. **Decision\u2011Making** \u2013 C excels (quick, correct decisions); A anticipates danger and sees complex connections; B assesses weather well; D solves problems extremely well.\n5. **Teamwork & Communication** \u2013 No candidate has a documented strength; the most severe negative interpersonal traits belong to B (uncooperative, grumpy) and D (arrogant, loner, moody). C\u2019s difficulty communicating ideas and egocentric attitude are drawbacks, but his expressed concern for others suggests a baseline safety\u2011oriented attitude that may be more manageable than outright uncooperativeness.\n6. **Professional Development** \u2013 B shows solid technical skill; C is reluctant to further education; A is not open to new ideas; D has no data.\n**Overall judgment**\nLong\u2011distance operations demand a 